Syrus ha'd sent off Demea, as he supposed, safely into the country, but Ctesipho is alarmed at the possible consequences of the trick. Syrus is suggesting a way out of the difficulty, when Demea appears in person, having accidentally heard that Ctesipho is not at his country house.

The ellipse of te, however, has a parallel in that of eum in 52 5 and in 608, the con· text in both cases making the sense certain: while to pass from indirect to direct speech, when the clauses are connected by a relative, would be scarcely possible.

528. in mente est. Here Δ. has in mentem, all other MSS. in mente, while in the parallel passage Heaut. 986 Δ. with D G read in mente, the other MSS. in mentem. The MS. authority being so evenly balanced, the reading most in harmony with ordinary syntax has been chosen.
